title: Teach a child to tell the time

description.text: The teaching clock can be a an interesting 3D printing project as it works as a teaching aid on 2 levels. The first is the obvious one, to teach young children to tell the time using a clock rather than reading the time from their phone. The second is that it uses a novel mechanism to create the 12:1 ratio between the Hour and Minute hands. A description of the Ferguson paradox can be found here http://www.woodenclocks.co.uk/page72.html on my woodenclocks website. This is a simple build with no requirements for supports, only some adjustment to get the right fits on the main shaft. The teaching Clock can be held using the round handle on the back, by either the teacher or the child, the hands can be turned to a time by the teacher to ask the child, or the child can turn the hands to answer the teacher's question. This is my second 3D printer project, I use a Zortrax M200 and I am just getting use to it. I am not sure that I can use the printer with sufficient confidence yet to advise anyone else on the settings to make the parts for this project. My first project was to build an actual Skeleton clock using the 3D printer after spending some years sticking to clock building in wood, if you want to see the 3D printed clock it is on the 3dprinterclocks website here. http://www.3dprintedclocks.com

comments.text:
HI brlaw, just a quick comment to suggest what I think would be an improvement to the clock. Instead of round sections on the main clock spindle, they can be made square (or a hexagonal if desired), the reason being that if they were square the hands would not have to be glued (or at least you would only need a dab or glue), neither would the arm that holds the planetary gears in place, it would be locked to the spindle shaft with the square acting as a key, both the hour hand on its gear, and the minute hand can both be locked onto the spindle with the square keys so to speak.
Even the tiny planetary gears could be held with square axles with only a small round section in the middle, I found that gluing the tiny gears in place was a bit of a fiddle as the superglue tended to flow about, the square keys may make it slightly easier to glue in place.
Other than that it's a great clock, I now have made six of them :o) Thanks for the design.

The final assembly is compact and solid enough to be carried everywhere. LED ring resistors are designed for a 3.6V supply, allowing use of a single 18650 cell or 3 AA NiMh cells in serie to power the system. LEDs used are stadard 10mm white LEDs with the tip filed.

LedRing and LedRingSupport assembly Use a 1 ~ 1.5mm drill bit to open the holes in led ring. If your printer is precise enough and your LED pins are small as mine, this should not be needed. title: Bearing Retainer PLUS Plunger Screw Adapter

description.text:
This is a modification and upgrade on the few derivatives of emmett's bearing retainer, such as johnboiles'. Like some others, I too wanted to have as much visibility to the plunger/bearing/filament feed area. This is for the MK5/MK6/MK6+ stepper acrylic face. So I trimmed as much material I could off the original design while keeping it rigid. Included the standoffs from johnboiles' design. BUT WAIT THERE'S MORE! Like some others I had the problem where the plunger screw keeps loosening and ruining my prints. Due to the filament being forced in forward and reverse rapidly for certain prints, it would result in the plunger screw becoming loose and the filament would stop extruding. I would have to go to town with kapton tape everywhere trying to keep that screw in place! I couldn't trust my printer for long periods of time without checking on it periodically. But everything is included in one part! So this part includes an arm that slides into the plunger screw area and fits snug around the screw shaft so it no longer loosens! Yeah! Save my kapton tape for more important uses now. Due to the tight tolerances in the plunger screw area, the hole may not print perfectly. Just grab some tweezers or an X-Acto blade and remove any extruded plastic that gets in the way. The plunger screw should insert fairly easily - you may need to use pliers to hold onto the screw as you rotate it in for the first time or your fingers might be raw after. I would suggest test inserting the plunger screw before bolting it onto the extruder so its easier once its actually installed. NEW IN VERSION 7!! (Took me 4 more revisions to get it juuuust right)
New and improved, this part adds additional support area where the plunger screw is inserted and more viewing area. New steps for v7 include removing the two nuts and bolts that are intended to hold the plunger nut in place. Since the adapter blocks the nut from falling out, these bolts aren't needed and allowed me to place in additional plunger screw support. Enjoy!

• Print thing

  • Unscrew plunger screw from side of stepper assembly
    • 2a. Unscrew the two nuts and bolts holding in the large plunger nut. Keep the large plunger nut in place.

  • Hold thing in front of stepper assembly and screw four M3x16 bolts into the unused nuts housed inside the stepper assembly.

  • Reinsert plunger screw and tighten plunger.

  • Print for hours on end in confidence!

Notes: I printed on glass bed starting at 65 degree's and dropped to 60 about 1/3rd the way through the 3mm thick fan side (which was on the print bed)
I have my nozzle feeler gauge set at 0.06mm off the build plate, My starting temp was 200deg, and ramped down to 198 for the main side print on the horizontal, as soon as we went vertical I got some wispy bits, and dropped the temp to 194 then 190 and settled on 189, this section is only 50mm long and 3mm wide, so it didn't have much time to cool, and my next print is the cooling fan and new rear print head bracket to hopefully over come this.

40MM L fan bracket I drew this object in Fusion 360, I am new to Fusion but love the simplicity and the ease of use.
Basically drew the larger portion on the Y plane two squares the main section and the side stiffener, placed the 38mm circle, drew a cross, offset the center lines by .75 with a 10mm center circle, from the outer edges of the circle I formed a box, where i placed the 4 x 4mm mounting holes, which subsequently placed the centered at exactly 32mm the dim i measured on my fan.
Out of the sketch into the body, pulled the main body by 3mm, pulled the second square by 3mm, then used a combination of fillets and chamfer's to shape the wavy support edge. Rotated the image so I was looking at the 3mm "base" started a new sketch in this plane, and drew 3 rectangles, 1 50 x 10, and two small 10 x 3 then used the arch tool to arch the upper end as this would give it self support as it printed. I then passed it directly off to print software. In this case Repitier, I am also trialing Cura.

This is a base added to StormTrooper Resculpt by Geoffro, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:362947/#made . On thingiverse antering page I could not chose the ''REMIX'' button. I wanted a stand for the helmet and , as I am using transparent filament I printed the whole thing painting only few particoular so that a led could light clearly . If you want the version with led ,
you will need ° led (the common leds work at 1.5 - 3 V )
° 300 Ohm resistor
° savaged electical wire
° rock switch (my drawing comes with 15 x 21 mm one) There are two STL file , one is for the stand with NO Led and one is for the mounting Led one , this means the base has the hole for the switch, as said a 15 x 21 mm rock switch .
Inside the stand there is a MN21 battery holder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1258021 glued on inner top surface , it is cabled like in the attached Jpeg scheme. Resistor can be mounted either on negative pole. Led pins polarity can be easily discovered by watching the two parts inside the plastic : the smaller one is always the + . You don't need solder , you can just weave cables together. Don't forget to print your StormTrooper helmet with low infill otherwise the Led won't be able to light inside the plastic . And afterall you have to make a hole inside the head , just use a 10-12 mm drill bit .

description.text:
I created this smaller version of the Longclaw Sword v2 by plrmaker7 to use as a decoration. It includes a few modifications from his hilt and pommel:
  • I scaled it down to 60% size to print more easily and be a nice size for a decoration
  • I cropped the blade near the hilt and added printing supports for the hand guard
  • I added a channel in the blade and hilt for a wood screw (3mm shaft, 7mm head) so it could be attached to a wall
  • I created a custom connector to "mate" the pommel and hilt
    • Although it looks like a coat hook, I don't recommend using it for that: It's probably not strong enough to hold much weight. I intend to hang conference name badges from the hilt and leave the pommel out so I don't put too much weight on the connector. The "chin" of the dire wolf didn't print right because it needs support but my slicer couldn't make that happen.

Collimate your telescope easily with a laser pointer. Basic idea is you put a laser pointer in one end, it bounces off the secondary mirror and hits the center of the primary mirror. The beam then reflects off the primary mirror back up to the eyepiece. When properly collimated, the laser should bounce right back into the laser pointer hole. The eyepiece size is 1.25" Here's a video showing how to use a commercial version.
http://youtu.be/N1asF3m2Mh0 This is a bit of a test. I'm not sure a 3d printed version will be accurate enough to properly collimate a telescope. I think it will also depend on the accuracy of cheap laser pointers.

This might print as a single piece as in the .stl below, but I think it'll need to be split into two pieces for the most accurate print job. It is meant to work with a cheap ~14mm dia. laser printer like this:
http://www.amazon.com/532nm-Astronomy-Powerful-Green-Pointer/dp/B0019D12WW You are welcome to try printing it as is if you like, and please add comments/suggestions.

comments.text: The collimator lenses have AR coatings designed for the specific wavelength of the laser, visible optics in a telescope have FAR different coatings and specifically the intent here was to get a reflection back at the laser. title: Parametric Carriage Base for V-Slot Printers

description.text:
I originally designed this openscad script to be used with my Emmett-Delta 3d printer that uses 2060 V-Slot for the Vertical columns & 3/4" EMT for the horizontal supports.  I took some extra time & made this parametric to facilitate changing it for different configurations.  It looks kind of like a dog bone in this setup, but you can change 17 different variables to make it in almost unlimited configurations.  The carriage that holds the belt and rods is a separate file, so you can use your own carriage.  You just need to have the module that draws the carriage named DrawCarriage()
The 1st variable in the file, W_X_Offset is the horizontal offset between the center line of the carriage & the wheel.  I use 39.9mm for use with 2060, 19.9mm for 2020, 29.9 for 2040 & 49.9 for 2080.  Those numbers work for me, but you might need to adjust them for your configuration.  Most of the variables should be described well, but you can easily change any to see how the part adjusts.  Sometimes you may have to change more than 1 variable to make the geometry work out as I did not program this to handle all the problems. Some cases just will not work, like trying to create the top or bottom side below outside diameter of the corner wheels.  You can put it flush with them though by setting any of the 3 variables, FlushTop, FlushBottom, FlushSides = 1.  The default height (Ht) is set to 6mm.  a minimum of 3 will work with ledges on.  You can go lower than that if you turn ledges off.  The maximum height is only limited to how thick you want it.
I like the dog bone style since it allows me to get a little more height on the carriage before hitting the end stops.  It also seems to be pretty strong having the curves & ledges.
Even though this was designed for V-Slot, you can probably use this design for a lot of other possibilities.
I drew this up in 2d 1st using DraftSight to see how the geometry looks and use the dimensions to work backward to get the formulas I need for the openscad script.

description.text:
I know there are many great designs out there, but some are hard to make, others are too flimsy, others require supports, screws and other stuff and I've made a design that requires 0 support, 0 screws and it's easy to print.
The only thing you need is a bit of glue and 5 minutes of assembly.
It's to be used with 25 mm diameter 45mm focal lenses available on either ebay or aliexpress.
For the hinge mechanism use PLA or ABS filament of 1.75mm. To hold the phone in place use rubber bands. It is made to fit most phones and I didn't design a proper lock mechanism due to different phone sizes.
It should take about 12 hours of printing on most printers or a bit more depending on your settings. I use 0.2 layer height and 30-35% infill.
Important note: Please be aware that this case is suited for phones up to 5.1 inches. If it's bigger than 5.5 inches it will exit the case a bit and the top part of the screen will not be fully viewable.
Enjoy.

description.text:
This is a beer bottle capper for standard (US) beer bottle caps. It should work on any non twist-off beer bottle. It was inspired by the capper described in this article, http://makezine.com/2011/09/13/tool-review-drill-press-bottle-capper/ . To use sit your bottle under the drill press with a cap on it. Sit the capper on top of the cap and press down with the drill press. You are basically just using the drill press as an arbor press. If it is the right size you will feel a reassuring pop and the cap will bottom out with the rim of the cap barely below the lip of the cup. It really doesn't take that much force. If you are worried that you might break the beer bottle, the capper is probably too small. There are two files.
BeerCapper_Final is the capper at the dimensions that I think it needs to be at. ID at base of the cup is 28mm. At the rim of the cup it is 29mm.
BeerCapper_Final_oversized is the capper with the IDs increased 1mm. This is what I actually used and tested. My printer was printing inner diameters small, so I just used this. You could also scale the parts. SolidWorks files are attached.
